1209 To be expended for the Bullying Prevention Project in accordance with Title
1210 16, Chapter 28B, Code of Alabama 1975. The State Superintendent of Education
1211 shall distribute the above appropriation as grants to local education
1212 agencies. These agencies may be awarded funds only after application to the
1213 State Department of Education. The grant application process may require the
1214 submission of plans by the applicant to meet the requirements set forth in
1215 Chapter 28B of Title 16. In the awarding of grants, preference will be given
1216 to applicants seeking to develop and implement evidence-based practices to
1217 promote a school environment that is free of harassment, intimidation,
1218 violence, and threats of violence. This program may also address tier one
1219 and tier two of the school-based mental health model of all students
1220 receiving prevention education and peers working to support and identify
1221 at-risk students. Additionally, the program may focus to increase school
1222 safety through early identification of at-risk students, minimizing
1223 disciplinary infractions including school suspensions and expulsions. The
1224 program may provide grade level prevention curriculum for all students and,
1225 in that case, the curriculum must be updated annually to remain current and
1226 relevant to current trends that youth face in their lives. Any applicable
1227 prevention curriculum must be comprehensive and satisfy the following state
1228 mandates: Erin's Law, Jamari Terrell Williams Student Bullying Prevention
1229 Act, Jason Flatt Act, Price Hornsby Act, and drugs and alcohol prevention
1230 programs. In addition, any program related to mental health should be
1231 flexible enough to focus on the greatest mental health needs for each
1232 individual school. For accountability purposes, reporting data must include
1233 the number of students engaged in the programs, the number of students
1234 supported, and the number of students referred to adults as at-risk.
