1269 This appropriation shall be used for the State Department of Education, in
1270 consultation with the Department of Early Childhood Education, to fund a
1271 program to be known as the Governor's Turnaround Schools. These grants are
1272 for the lowest performing public elementary schools which are identified as
1273 underperforming by the State Superintendent in consideration of the
1274 provisions of the Alabama Accountability Act, the State Report Card System,
1275 and other criteria as determined by the State Superintendent. The intent of
1276 these grants is to identify and target specific deficiencies of each
1277 individual underperforming elementary school and target said deficiencies
1278 with high quality and innovative educational supports. In consultation with
1279 these schools as well as the local education agencies that respectively
1280 oversee these schools, the State Department of Education will develop and
1281 oversee a comprehensive plan for school improvement. It is the intention of
1282 this provision that all areas of the State Department, including Alabama
1283 Reading Initiative, Alabama Math, Science, and Technology Initiative, Office
1284 of Mathematics Improvement, and Office of School Improvement, will work
1285 together to best serve these selected schools. Schools previously named to
1286 this list will be known as Cohort 1. Beginning with the fiscal year 2027
1287 Budget Request, the State Department will recommend a pathway for schools in
1288 Cohort 1 to exit this program, and the Department will recommend new schools
1289 to replace those exiting the program in subsequent years. These schools may
1290 be known as Cohort 2 and so forth. The State Superintendent may also request
1291 additional funds so that additional cohorts can be expanded as Cohort 1
1292 schools leave the program over the next few years. Any expansion of new
1293 Cohorts should be modest with respect to the purpose of this program which
1294 is expected to offer extraordinary supports to a relatively limited number
1295 of schools at a time. The State Department of Education should annually
1296 produce written progress reports on these schools to the Chair of the House
1297 Ways and Means - Education Committee, the Chair of the Senate Finance and
1298 Taxation - Education Committee, the Governor, and the Local School Board,
